27:36.520 --> 27:41.520
Usually when we say free speech, adults know the limits. You know that there are libel limits.

27:41.520 --> 27:48.520
There's Brandenburg versus Ohio. There are all sorts of things that you can't say or do.

27:48.520 --> 27:57.520
We have export controls. In fact, in physics, there's a concept called restricted data

27:57.520 --> 28:02.520
where if you have an idea and you're not a federal employee and you don't have a security clearance,

28:02.520 --> 28:11.520
if the idea touches nuclear weapons, you may not share it at all because it is born secret.

28:11.520 --> 28:15.520
There are huge limits on speech that are part of free speech.

28:15.520 --> 28:23.520
So when we say free speech, I'm 100% for free speech, but that is an understanding that that's a reserved term of art.

28:23.520 --> 28:30.520
It's not unrestricted speech. It has never been. It can't exist as such.

28:30.520 --> 28:36.520
You and I think are both big fans of Elon Musk. I had an interview with him at the start of the year

28:36.520 --> 28:43.520
which he unceremoniously cancelled when he found a clip of me on the show mildly criticising his decision

28:43.520 --> 28:48.520
to let Alex Jones back onto X having previously said he would never let him back on

28:48.520 --> 28:53.520
and he wouldn't let people who stand on the graves of dead children on the platform.

28:53.520 --> 28:57.520
I thought he was wrong to change his mind about Alex Jones, but I found it quite ironic

28:57.520 --> 29:06.520
that Elon, who is a constant promoter of free speech, particularly on X, would not want to engage in an interview with me

29:06.520 --> 29:10.520
because I criticised him over something like that.

29:10.520 --> 29:16.520
Well, you know, everyone wants to date free speech, but when free speech wants to date other people,

29:16.520 --> 29:23.520
we always have second thoughts and I'd like to think that I'm at least self-aware enough to realise

29:23.520 --> 29:31.520
that most of the things that we stand up for, truth, ethics, free speech, etc., when they bind on us,

29:31.520 --> 29:36.520
we as humans are very likely to change our mind. That's why we try to enshrine this in law.

29:36.520 --> 29:42.520
It's sort of a Ulysses contract that I know that I'm going to be against free speech when it's used in a way that I don't like.

29:42.520 --> 29:48.520
I bristled when you said you read my Wikipedia entry because I have idiots who constantly try to deface it.

29:49.520 --> 29:53.520
On the other hand, because I'm locked into a free speech mentality,

29:53.520 --> 29:58.520
it stays my hand when I try to say that that's something that shouldn't be permitted.

29:58.520 --> 30:05.520
Effectively, I have to put up with the empowerment of idiots and dangerous ones at that

30:05.520 --> 30:09.520
if I'm really signed up for the free speech project and, you know, there you have it.

30:09.520 --> 30:13.520
It was interesting on Wikipedia. I mean, my eldest son noticed, I don't know if you know if it's still there,

30:13.520 --> 30:17.520
if I never look at it, but it said that I was the youngest of four children

30:17.520 --> 30:22.520
and I happened to be the oldest of four children. So it's a tiny little fact.

30:22.520 --> 30:25.520
It doesn't matter to anybody other than it's wrong.

30:25.520 --> 30:28.520
So my eldest son as a journalist corrected it.

30:28.520 --> 30:32.520
And then whoever it was who put the erroneous information up there,

30:32.520 --> 30:37.520
re-corrected it back to the false one. And this went on and on and on and on,

30:37.520 --> 30:39.520
and there was no end to it.

30:39.520 --> 30:42.520
Where my eldest son kept saying I was the eldest.

30:42.520 --> 30:46.520
And whoever this person was kept saying I was the youngest.

30:46.520 --> 30:51.520
And all it showed me was that Wikipedia professes to be, you know,

30:51.520 --> 30:57.520
a great vehicle for information, accurate information about people and so on and free speech and so on.

30:57.520 --> 31:02.520
But there's not much it can do if someone is utterly determined to put disinformation out there.

31:02.520 --> 31:05.520
Well, it was briefly a great resource.

31:05.520 --> 31:09.520
The problem that we find is it had certain flaws.

31:09.520 --> 31:12.520
When you had rules about, you know, authoritative sources,

31:12.520 --> 31:16.520
and sources were in fact largely authoritative, it worked well.

31:16.520 --> 31:21.520
As you've seen the degradation of authoritative sources and as people become more sophisticated

31:21.520 --> 31:26.520
about what kinds of exploits work on Wikipedia, you have a very dangerous situation,

31:26.520 --> 31:30.520
which is that technical articles continue to be of fairly high quality

31:30.520 --> 31:34.520
because there's no one determined to graffiti over them.

31:34.520 --> 31:42.520
However, when you start including political people or people who are disliked by someone,

31:42.520 --> 31:50.520
the incentives change and as a result what you see is a sort of a chimeric resource,

31:50.520 --> 31:55.520
which is very high quality if it was going to describe hydraulic presses, let's say,

31:55.520 --> 32:01.520
but very low quality when you have a controversial figure who's hated by a determined group.

32:01.520 --> 32:06.520
So I think that it has morphed over our lifetime from being something

32:06.520 --> 32:12.520
which is an astonishing achievement to something which is in fact very dangerous.

32:12.520 --> 32:18.520
The other thing I would say is that we have a very strange situation

32:18.520 --> 32:24.520
in that we expected that free speech was going to be the exchange of ideas with which we disagreed.

32:24.520 --> 32:32.520
And instead it has morphed, I think, over my lifetime much more into a question of what can I get away with

32:32.520 --> 32:37.520
that might not be true, it might not be a different point of view,

32:37.520 --> 32:42.520
but it's simply a free speech exploit to destroy.

32:42.520 --> 32:44.520
If I don't have a good argument against somebody's position,

32:44.520 --> 32:50.520
I always have the ability to try to talk about that person's family or skin care or what have you.

32:50.520 --> 32:55.520
And I think that for many of us we're sort of waking up to the idea

32:55.520 --> 33:00.520
that a world saturated in speech without friction, which is what we now have,

33:00.520 --> 33:05.520
you don't have to print a pamphlet or get a book deal in order to say your piece,

33:05.520 --> 33:13.520
that in a cacophonous world, mostly what free speech produces is vitriol and personal attacks.

33:13.520 --> 33:18.520
And I think that we're all sort of scratching our head, this isn't exactly the future that we had envisaged.

